Ex libris. Gilbert R. Redgrave The Elms Beckenham, Kent. Feb. 1895 Note
This is a fine copy of the first illustrated edition of Euclid, and it is probably the most magnificent work of the series produced by E. Ratdolt during his stay at Venice, from 1476 to 1486. It is No 26 of my "Bibliography" of this period of Ratdolt's activity. The leatherwork of the cover was designed and executed by me, and the binding is by Lachnsdorf. G.R.R.
[Dated lated 19th-century ms. ownership inscription and bibliographical note of Gilbert Richard Redgrave (1844-1941), English architect, art historian and bibliographer. With Alfred W. [Late 16th- or early 17th-century ms. ownership inscription of Franciscus Ligniceus of Šibenik, Croatia, son of Helias, doctor of theology at Padua and archdeacon of Zadar (75 km. north of Šibenik). He is named in a document from the episcopate of Minuccio Minucci of Zadar (1596-1604) as "ludi magister" (schoolmaster); cf. A. Marani, ed., Atti pastorali di Minuccio Minucci arcivescovo di Zara (1596-1604) (Rome: Edizioni di storia e letteratura, 1970), p. 7. His presence at Padua is attested by the university's records surrounding his examination in theology on 8 June 1600, in which he is identified as Franciscus Ligniceus Sibiniceus archidiaconus Iadrensis f. olim magn. d. Eliae; cf. E. M. Forin, ed., Acta Graduum Academicorum Gymnasii Patavini ab anno 1566 ad annum 1600 (Rome: Editrice Antenore, 2008), no. 3563. He is probably to be identified with the humanist Franje Linjičića [in Latin, Franciscus Ligniceus], whose poem "In detractorem superiorum carminum" is preserved in the ms. Varia Dalmatica (Zadar, Science Library, shelf no. 253290, MS 617), which contains a number of works by authors from Šibenik. Cf. N. Jovanović, "Rukopisni zbornik Varia Dalmatica (Codex Lucianus) kao svjedočanstvo humanističke književne komunikacije," Colloquia Maruliana 17.17 (April 2008): 43-55.]

comment.text: Francisci lignicei siben. Helie filij [...] [...] Theolog. Docto. Patauini. [Partially illegible early (16th-century?) ms. ownership inscription of Franciscus Ligniceus, son of Helias, doctor of theology at Padua. The bookseller's description accompanying this volume suggests the vernacular version of the surname might be Formschneider or Taglialegna. However, if the toponym "siben." is to be read Sibenicensis (i.e. of Šibenik in central Dalmatia, Croatia), then Ligniceus is possibly to be identified with the humanist Franje Linjičića, whose poem "In detractorem superiorum carminum" is preserved in the ms. Varia Dalmatica (Zadar, Science Library, shelf no. 253290, MS 617), which contains a number of works by authors from Šibenik. Cf. N. Jovanović, "Rukopisni zbornik Varia Dalmatica (Codex Lucianus) kao svjedočanstvo humanističke književne komunikacije," Colloquia Maruliana 17.17 (April 2008): 43-55.]

comment.text: Armorial bookplate of George Dawson Coleman (1825-1878), American ironmaster, politician and philanthropist. comment.text: Bookplate of Georg Kloss (1787-1854), physician, historian, bibliographer and book collector. He studied at Heidelberg and Göttingen (where he helped to found the Corps Hannovera Göttingen), receiving his medical degree from the latter and beginning to practice in Frankfurt in 1810. He collected mss. and books, including incunables; a Freemason, he also acquired an extensive library of Masonic works. A portion of his library was sold at auction in London by Sotheby's in 1835; a further sale took place in New York under the aegis of Cooley and Bangs in 1838. The ms. note here ("No 2874 in his Catalogue") refers to the Sotheby's auction; cf. Catalogue of the Library of Dr. Kloss of Franckfort a. M. (London: S. Sotheby & Son, 1835). Established heading: Kloss, Georg Franz Burkhard, 1787-1854

comment.text: Metelli Crispolti [Ms. ownership inscription of Metello Crispolti. The Crispolti appear to have been a Perugian family. This book-owning scion has an unenlightening entry ("Crispolti, Metelli, et amicorum") in the IPI. A letter dated 3 January 1585 from a Metello Crispolti to a correspondent in Rome regarding the ordering and borrowing of books is recorded among the mss. of the Biblioteca Augusta in Perugia (cf. G. Cecchini, La Biblioteca Augusta del comune di Perugia (Rome: Edizione di storia et letteratura, 1978), p. 355). Given that we also have Crispolti's ownership inscription (as Metello Crispolti and friends) on a 1584 Florentine edition of Girolamo Borro's De peripatetica docendi atque addiscendi methodo, I'm thinking there's a strong possibility that the two might be one and the same person.]

comment.text: Binding: Early full blind-tooled parchment(?) over square-edge wooden boards; 3 raised bands on spine; evidence of 2 leather and metal clasps and metal catchplates; ms. fore-edge title ("LIB. AETHICORum F. Geraldi Odonis"); two paper leaves from an incunable edition of the works of Virgil (Venice: Thomas de Blavis, de Alexandria, 24 Dec. 1484; ISTC iv00176000) used as binder's waste (front pastedown: leaf C6, recto visible, with text of Aeneid XII, lines 504-533, surrounded by Servius's commentary; back pastedown: leaf C5, verso visible, with text of Aeneid XII, lines 460-503, accompanied by Servius's commentary); small portions of early parchment ms. leaves used as binder's waste (reinforcement at center of most gatherings). Pictured here: Right board.
